Last week, when Imax C.E.O. Rich Gelfond presented the company=E2=80=99s la=
test quarterly
earnings report=E2=80=94which fell short of Wall Street expectations and ca=
used the stock to dip 5 percent in after-hours trading=E2=80=94he had some =
additional, exciting news to discuss: Netflix had committed to showing Gret=
a Gerwig=E2=80=99s upcoming Narnia film on at least 1,000 Imax screens for =
an exclusive two-week run starting on Thanksgiving weekend 2026. Netflix wo=
uld then wait two weeks before debuting the film on Christmas Day. The only=
 problem? Theater owners and studio execs, who
are kind of essential to Imax=E2=80=99s business, wanted to throttle him.

Netflix=E2=80=99s insistence on putting its movies directly on the streamer=
, with some exceptions that get brief theatrical releases to qualify for fe=
stivals and awards, is all too well known to both studios and exhibitors. B=
ut Gerwig, like many directors, wants audiences to have a chance to see her=
 film on the big screen first. And because Greta gets what Greta wants, as =
she should, the Imax deal was born. In a February 19 call
with analysts, Gelfond talked about the heavy lifting required to reach tha=
t agreement. =E2=80=9CObviously, there=E2=80=99s a lot of different constit=
uencies with different agendas,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CSo we really had=
 to construct something that would work for the exhibitors, that would work=
 for Greta, that would work for Netflix, that would work for a lot of peopl=
e. The right amount of windows. The right amount of playtime. =E2=80=A6 It=
=E2=80=99s a fairly complex deal to have met all the various constituencies=
=2E=E2=80=9D

The
Netflix-Imax deal, however, didn=E2=80=99t work for the legacy studios and =
theater chains that regard Netflix as their =E2=80=9Ccommon enemy,=E2=80=9D=
 as one studio veteran told me. According to sources, some of the studios h=
ad vehemently pressed Imax not to do this deal. Imax=E2=80=99s most importa=
nt partner, Disney, is especially furious given the many millions of dollar=
s its megahits have put into Imax=E2=80=99s coffers. =E2=80=9CRich did this=
 on his own without consulting any of his [studio] partners,=E2=80=9D an in=
sider said. =E2=80=9CThey gave
Netflix a two-week exclusive even though the other studios provide movies t=
o them 52 weeks a year.=E2=80=9D

Disney also has an opening-date marker on Thanksgiving 2026 for an unspecif=
ied animated film, which=E2=80=94if it turns out that the studio really has=
 a movie ready for that slot=E2=80=94would be deprived of an extra-profitab=
le Imax run during the holidays. (Last time Disney put a marker on that dat=
e, the movie turned out to be Moana 2, which grossed a modest $1 billion.) =
A couple weeks earlier,
on November 6, 2026, Disney has an untitled Marvel movie slated. Lionsgate,=
 meanwhile, has a Hunger Games prequel set to open on November 20, and undo=
ubtedly would like more than a few days on Imax screens.

And despite Gelfond=E2=80=99s claim that he had won over the =E2=80=9Cvario=
us constituencies,=E2=80=9D multiple sources told me that some of the large=
st theater chains in North America=E2=80=94including Regal and Cinemark=E2=
=80=94were caught off guard and are so angry that they are indicating, at l=
east for now, that
they won=E2=80=99t play Narnia on the Imax screens in their theaters. That =
may be a plausible threat. As one exhibition exec observed, after pandemic-=
 and strike-related supply delays, there are now more movies in the pipelin=
e that could bring profit and play on all of a chain=E2=80=99s screens, lar=
ge and small. For theater owners, this two-week Netflix stunt, he said, =E2=
=80=9Cis not anything that=E2=80=99s sustainable in any shape or form.=E2=
=80=9D

The Nuclear Option
------------------

So=E2=80=A6 can theaters refuse to play the Gerwig film on their Imax scree=
ns? The answer would appear to
be yes. While Imax licenses its technology to theater chains, multiple exhi=
bition and studio sources told me that the chains ultimately control what g=
ets booked on those giant screens. Another source said that both Netflix an=
d Gerwig=E2=80=99s reps were concerned about this very threat.

But Gelfond assured both that he had a =E2=80=9Cnuclear option=E2=80=9D to =
ensure that theaters will cooperate and book the film. What specifically th=
at might be was unclear to the many sources I asked. When I put the
question to Imax, the company responded with a statement that doubled down =
on the premise: =E2=80=9CUnder our theater agreements, Imax requires exhibi=
tors to play the films we format and program. Our ability to curate our pro=
gramming is what makes us valuable to exhibitors, filmmakers, and studios, =
and delivers a return on investment with our theaters worldwide.=E2=80=9D

While the issue might seem like a see-you-in-court situation, that outcome =
is probably unlikely. Sources believe that Imax has already
cut a deal with AMC Theatres, which has 182 Imax screens in the U.S.=E2=80=
=94far more than any other company=E2=80=94and often doesn=E2=80=99t march =
in lockstep with other exhibitors. (Reached by phone, AMC C.E.O. Adam Aron =
said it was =E2=80=9Cinappropriate=E2=80=9D for him to comment.) Also, what=
 happens in 2026 is all hypothetical at this point, anyway. Even if the oth=
er top exhibitors=E2=80=94which together account for about 108 Imax screens=
 out of roughly 400 in North America=E2=80=94are mad now, that doesn=E2=80=
=99t mean they won=E2=80=99t
eventually crack to get a couple of weeks=E2=80=99 worth of revenue from wh=
at might be another Gerwig event movie, especially if it picks up good earl=
y buzz.

It=E2=80=99s not like the big theater chains haven=E2=80=99t played ball wi=
th Netflix before: AMC, Regal, and Cinemark all showed Rian Johnson=E2=80=
=99s Glass Onion: A Knives Out Mystery during its very limited, weeklong ru=
n in about 600 theaters in November 2022, no doubt hoping that a taste of b=
ox office cash would whet Netflix=E2=80=99s
appetite for more. Netflix didn=E2=80=99t disclose box office numbers from =
the run, but David A. Gross of Franchise Entertainment Research told Variet=
y that he believed the Knives Out sequel would have opened at around $30 mi=
llion domestically and pulled in $300 million worldwide had it been given a=
 full theatrical run.

Netflix=E2=80=99s appetite was not whetted, much to the frustration of the =
filmmakers and exhibitors. =E2=80=9CBy their own account, they thought they=
 left
money on the table,=E2=80=9D said Cinemark C.E.O. Sean Gamble at an investo=
r conference in March 2023. =E2=80=9CWe certainly were disappointed they di=
dn=E2=80=99t take advantage of a more significant theatrical release, just =
based on the overwhelming consumer demand.=E2=80=9D Still, he called the ex=
periment =E2=80=9Ca positive step=E2=80=9D and expressed hope that, in time=
, Netflix would see the value of larger theatrical releases.

=E2=80=9CIn Bed With the
Devil=E2=80=9D
------------------

Of course, when the Narnia deal was announced, most of the town immediately=
 began to hope that it
might represent a shift in Netflix=E2=80=99s longstanding policy against pu=
tting its movies in theaters. But co-C.E.O. Ted Sarandos shot that down imm=
ediately, saying the deal represented =E2=80=9Cno change at all=E2=80=9D to=
 the streamer=E2=80=99s strategy.

Many in Hollywood are baffled by Netflix=E2=80=99s steadfast commitment to =
this filmmaker-unfriendly position. Scott Stuber, when he was chairman of N=
etflix Films, was openly warring with Sarandos on the issue before he left =
the company
last year. That=E2=80=99s because a hit movie that gets a high-profile mark=
eting push and plays for weeks in theaters can bring in big box office doll=
ars and lead to a waterfall of money as the film progresses through various=
 release windows and platforms. These days, Netflix can be part of that wat=
erfall as studios license movies to the service after they=E2=80=99ve playe=
d on other platforms. (=E2=80=9CSometimes you get in bed with the devil,=E2=
=80=9D as one studio executive put it.) With luck, a hit movie can launch a
franchise and, critically important to Disney and NBCUniversal, a hit movie=
 can also become a cultural phenomenon that sells a lot of merchandise and =
inspires new theme park attractions. Movies that have gone straight to stre=
aming have yet to generate anything near that kind of impact.

As one frustrated agent noted, the streamer that ate Hollywood has already =
broken its own policy vows: that there would never be ads, for example, or =
that the streamer would never go into sports. Why draw
the line at giving at least some movies full theatrical runs? Theater owner=
s are baffled. =E2=80=9CThis has been a perplexing misdirection from Netfli=
x in exhibitors=E2=80=99 minds for years,=E2=80=9D says a veteran theater e=
xecutive. =E2=80=9CExhibitors are kind of fed up with Netflix sticking thei=
r toe in the water and pulling back. Apple and Amazon have tried real theat=
rical runs, with mixed success. But they made a real attempt, and Netflix n=
ever has.=E2=80=9D

Meanwhile, a top executive at one chain predicts theater owners
may well follow through on their threat and decline to play Narnia. With mo=
re movies in the marketplace now, it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ca different ball ga=
me=E2=80=9D than with Glass Onion in 2022, he said, adding, =E2=80=9CI stru=
ggle to see who would program Narnia over Moana 3, if that were to come out=
=2E These large formats still only acco=
unt for less than 20 percent of box of=
fice. It=E2=80=99s not something that really works for our industry to supp=
ort that=E2=80=94particularly with a studio that is not in our
business.=E2=80=9D

So while it remains to be seen how Narnia will fare in Imax, let=E2=80=99s =
at least take a moment to celebrate the fact that a female director, of whi=
ch there are but few, has the clout to command a wide theatrical release fr=
om Netflix. From Lady Bird to Little Women to Barbie, Gerwig=E2=80=99s movi=
es have not only been critically acclaimed but have grossed a combined $1.9=
 billion, and not a dud in the lot. Whatever happens in this Imax
skirmish, no one will blame her for the plan, though a knowledgeable source=
 says Gerwig got interested in locking up some Imax screens because Warner =
Bros. couldn=E2=80=99t book any for Barbie thanks to Chris Nolan, who hoove=
red them up for Oppenheimer. That was a sore subject for Tom Cruise, too; h=
e couldn=E2=80=99t find room on the giant screens for the seventh (and very=
 expensive) Mission: Impossible film, which underperformed at the box
office with a global take of $571 million. Come to think of it, while Barbi=
e didn=E2=80=99t open on a single Imax screen, either, it still managed to =
do okay, raking in $1.5 billion on garden-variety movie screens.

