n Imax C.E.O. <strong>Rich Gelfond</strong> presented the company=E2=80=99s=
 latest quarterly
earnings report=E2=80=94which fell short of Wall Street expectations and ca=
used the stock to dip 5 percent in after-hours trading=E2=80=94he had some =
additional, exciting news to discuss: Netflix had committed to showing <str=
ong>Greta Gerwig</strong>=E2=80=99s upcoming <em>Narnia</em> film on at lea=
st 1,000 Imax screens for an exclusive two-week run starting on Thanksgivin=
g weekend 2026. Netflix would then wait two weeks before debuting the film =
on Christmas Day. The only problem? Theater owners and studio execs, who
are kind of essential to Imax=E2=80=99s business, wanted to throttle him.<b=
r/><br/>Netflix=E2=80=99s insistence on putting its movies directly on the =
streamer, with some exceptions that get brief theatrical releases to qualif=
y for festivals and awards, is all too well known to both studios and exhib=
itors. But Gerwig, like many directors, wants audiences to have a chance to=
 see her film on the big screen first. And because Greta gets what Greta wa=
nts, as she should, the Imax deal was born. In a February 19 call
with analysts, Gelfond talked about the heavy lifting required to reach tha=
t agreement. =E2=80=9CObviously, there=E2=80=99s a lot of different constit=
uencies with different agendas,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CSo we really had=
 to construct something that would work for the exhibitors, that would work=
 for Greta, that would work for Netflix, that would work for a lot of peopl=
e. The right amount of windows. The right amount of playtime. =E2=80=A6 It=
=E2=80=99s a fairly complex deal to have met all the various constituencies=
=2E=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>The
Netflix-Imax deal, however, didn=E2=80=99t <em>work</em> for the legacy stu=
dios and theater chains that regard Netflix as their =E2=80=9Ccommon enemy,=
=E2=80=9D as one studio veteran told me. According to sources, some of the =
studios had vehemently pressed Imax not to do this deal. Imax=E2=80=99s mos=
t important partner, Disney, is especially furious given the many millions =
of dollars its megahits have put into Imax=E2=80=99s coffers. =E2=80=9CRich=
 did this on his own without consulting any of his [studio] partners,=E2=80=
=9D an insider said. =E2=80=9CThey gave
Netflix a two-week exclusive even though the other studios provide movies t=
o them 52 weeks a year.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Disney also has an opening-date m=
arker on Thanksgiving 2026 for an unspecified animated film, which=E2=80=94=
if it turns out that the studio really has a movie ready for that slot=E2=
=80=94would be deprived of an extra-profitable Imax run during the holidays=
=2E (Last time Disney put a marker on t=
hat date, the movie turned out to be <=
em>Moana 2</em>, which grossed a modest $1 billion.) A couple weeks earlier=
,
on November 6, 2026, Disney has an untitled Marvel movie slated. Lionsgate,=
 meanwhile, has a <em>Hunger Games</em> prequel set to open on November 20,=
 and undoubtedly would like more than a few days on Imax screens.<br/><br/>=
And despite Gelfond=E2=80=99s claim that he had won over the =E2=80=9Cvario=
us constituencies,=E2=80=9D multiple sources told me that some of the large=
st theater chains in North America=E2=80=94including Regal and Cinemark=E2=
=80=94were caught off guard and are so angry that they are indicating, at l=
east for now, that
they won=E2=80=99t play <em>Narnia</em> on the Imax screens in their theate=
rs. That may be a plausible threat. As one exhibition exec observed, after =
pandemic- and strike-related supply delays, there are now more movies in th=
e pipeline that could bring profit and play on all of a chain=E2=80=99s scr=
eens, large and small. For theater owners, this two-week Netflix stunt, he =
said, =E2=80=9Cis not anything that=E2=80=99s sustainable in any shape or f=
orm.=E2=80=9D</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
