e:0pt;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;text-align:center;width=
:100%;"><h3 style=3D"margin:0;color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;=
PuckSerifDisplay&#39;,&#39;Georgia&#39;;font-size:24px;font-weight:400;lett=
er-spacing:normal;line-height:120%;text-align:center;margin-top:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0;mso-line-height-alt:28.799999999999997px;"><strong>The Nuclear Optio=
n</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"><div style=
=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;">So=E2=80=A6 <e=
m>can</em> theaters refuse to play the Gerwig film on their Imax screens? T=
he answer would appear to
be yes. While Imax licenses its technology to theater chains, multiple exhi=
bition and studio sources told me that the chains ultimately control what g=
ets booked on those giant screens. Another source said that both Netflix an=
d Gerwig=E2=80=99s reps were concerned about this very threat.<br/><br/>But=
 Gelfond assured both that he had a =E2=80=9Cnuclear option=E2=80=9D to ens=
ure that theaters will cooperate and book the film. What <em>specifically</=
em> that might be was unclear to the many sources I asked. When I put the
question to Imax, the company responded with a statement that doubled down =
on the premise: =E2=80=9CUnder our theater agreements, Imax requires exhibi=
tors to play the films we format and program. Our ability to curate our pro=
gramming is what makes us valuable to exhibitors, filmmakers, and studios, =
and delivers a return on investment with our theaters worldwide.=E2=80=9D<b=
r/><br/>While the issue might seem like a see-you-in-court situation, that =
outcome is probably unlikely. Sources believe that Imax has already
cut a deal with AMC Theatres, which has 182 Imax screens in the U.S.=E2=80=
=94far more than any other company=E2=80=94and often doesn=E2=80=99t march =
in lockstep with other exhibitors. (Reached by phone, AMC C.E.O. <strong>Ad=
am Aron</strong> said it was =E2=80=9Cinappropriate=E2=80=9D for him to com=
ment.) Also, what happens in 2026 is all hypothetical at this point, anyway=
=2E Even if the other top exhibitors=
=E2=80=94which together account for about=
 108 Imax screens out of roughly 400 in North America=E2=80=94are mad now, =
that doesn=E2=80=99t mean they won=E2=80=99t
eventually crack to get a couple of weeks=E2=80=99 worth of revenue from wh=
at might be another Gerwig event movie, especially if it picks up good earl=
y buzz.<br/><br/>It=E2=80=99s not like the big theater chains haven=E2=80=
=99t played ball with Netflix before: AMC, Regal, and Cinemark all showed <=
strong>Rian Johnson</strong>=E2=80=99s <em>Glass Onion: A Knives Out Myster=
y</em> during its very limited, weeklong run in about 600 theaters in Novem=
ber 2022, no doubt hoping that a taste of box office cash would whet Netfli=
x=E2=80=99s
appetite for more. Netflix didn=E2=80=99t disclose box office numbers from =
the run, but <strong>David A. Gross</strong> of Franchise Entertainment Res=
earch told <em>Variety</em> that he believed the <em>Knives Out </em>sequel=
 would have opened at around $30 million domestically and pulled in $300 mi=
llion worldwide had it been given a full theatrical run.<br/><br/>Netflix=
=E2=80=99s appetite was not whetted, much to the frustration of the filmmak=
ers and exhibitors. =E2=80=9CBy their own account, they thought they left
money on the table,=E2=80=9D said Cinemark C.E.O. <strong>Sean Gamble </str=
ong>at an investor conference in March 2023. =E2=80=9CWe certainly were dis=
appointed they didn=E2=80=99t take advantage of a more significant theatric=
al release, just based on the overwhelming consumer demand.=E2=80=9D Still,=
 he called the experiment =E2=80=9Ca positive step=E2=80=9D and expressed h=
ope that, in time, Netflix would see the value of larger theatrical release=
s.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
