:100%;"><h3 style=3D"margin:0;color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;=
PuckSerifDisplay&#39;,&#39;Georgia&#39;;font-size:24px;font-weight:400;lett=
er-spacing:normal;line-height:120%;text-align:center;margin-top:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0;mso-line-height-alt:28.799999999999997px;"><strong>=E2=80=9CIn Bed W=
ith the
Devil=E2=80=9D</strong>
</h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"><div style=
=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;">Of course, whe=
n the <em>Narnia</em> deal was announced, most of the town immediately bega=
n to hope that it
might represent a shift in Netflix=E2=80=99s longstanding policy against pu=
tting its movies in theaters. But co-C.E.O. <strong>Ted Sarandos</strong> s=
hot that down immediately, saying the deal represented =E2=80=9Cno change a=
t all=E2=80=9D to the streamer=E2=80=99s strategy.<br/><br/>Many in Hollywo=
od are baffled by Netflix=E2=80=99s steadfast commitment to this filmmaker-=
unfriendly position. <strong>Scott Stuber</strong>, when he was chairman of=
 Netflix Films, was openly warring with Sarandos on the issue before he lef=
t the company
last year. That=E2=80=99s because a hit movie that gets a high-profile mark=
eting push and plays for weeks in theaters can bring in big box office doll=
ars and lead to a waterfall of money as the film progresses through various=
 release windows and platforms. These days, Netflix can be part of that wat=
erfall as studios license movies to the service after they=E2=80=99ve playe=
d on other platforms. (=E2=80=9CSometimes you get in bed with the devil,=E2=
=80=9D as one studio executive put it.) With luck, a hit movie can launch a
franchise and, critically important to Disney and NBCUniversal, a hit movie=
 can also become a cultural phenomenon that sells a lot of merchandise and =
inspires new theme park attractions. Movies that have gone straight to stre=
aming have yet to generate anything near that kind of impact.<br/><br/>As o=
ne frustrated agent noted, the streamer that ate Hollywood has already brok=
en its own policy vows: that there would never be ads, for example, or that=
 the streamer would never go into sports. Why draw
the line at giving at least some movies full theatrical runs? Theater owner=
s are baffled. =E2=80=9CThis has been a perplexing misdirection from Netfli=
x in exhibitors=E2=80=99 minds for years,=E2=80=9D says a veteran theater e=
xecutive. =E2=80=9CExhibitors are kind of fed up with Netflix sticking thei=
r toe in the water and pulling back. Apple and Amazon have tried real theat=
rical runs, with mixed success. But they made a real attempt, and Netflix n=
ever has.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Meanwhile, a top executive at one chain predict=
s theater owners
may well follow through on their threat and decline to play <em>Narnia</em>=
=2E With more movies in the marke=
tplace now, it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ca differen=
t ball game=E2=80=9D than with <em>Glass Onion</em> in 2022, he said, addin=
g, =E2=80=9CI struggle to see who would program <em>Narnia</em> over <em>Mo=
ana 3,</em> if that were to come out. These large formats still only accoun=
t for less than 20 percent of box office. It=E2=80=99s not something that r=
eally works for our industry to support that=E2=80=94particularly with a st=
udio that is not in our
business.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>So while it remains to be seen how <em>Narnia</=
em> will fare in Imax, let=E2=80=99s at least take a moment to celebrate th=
e fact that a female director, of which there are but few, has the clout to=
 command a wide theatrical release <em>from Netflix</em>. From <em>Lady Bir=
d</em> to <em>Little Women</em> to <em>Barbie</em>, Gerwig=E2=80=99s movies=
 have not only been critically acclaimed but have grossed a combined $1.9 <=
em>billion</em>, and not a dud in the lot. Whatever happens in this Imax
skirmish, no one will blame her for the plan, though a knowledgeable source=
 says Gerwig got interested in locking up some Imax screens because Warner =
Bros. couldn=E2=80=99t book any for <em>Barbie </em>thanks to <strong>Chris=
 Nolan</strong>, who hoovered them up for <em>Oppenheimer</em>. That was a =
sore subject for <strong>Tom Cruise</strong>, too; he couldn=E2=80=99t find=
 room on the giant screens for the seventh (and <em>very</em> expensive) <e=
m>Mission: Impossible</em> film, which underperformed at the box
office with a global take of $571 million. Come to think of it, while <em>B=
arbie</em> didn=E2=80=99t open on a single Imax screen, either, it still ma=
naged to do okay, raking in $1.5 billion on garden-variety movie screens.</=
p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
